y = m1x1 + m2x2 = c instead of y = mx + c i.e.allow for multiple predictors (X).

the data

library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(mosaicData)

Can we explain the variation in volume using other predictors?

potential predictors: -temp (fahrenheit) -season -cloudcover (0-10) -precipitation (inches) -weekday

issues with data in raw form: -spring to fall are numbers rather than logical -some collinear predictors (3 temp predictors & 2 for weekday & all seasons (remove 1)) - we want all predictors to be independent

###variable engineering -drop collinear columns -convert column types -clean names

###detect perfect collinearity (column aliases)

alias(volume ~ ., RailTrail)

Model :
volume ~ hightemp + lowtemp + avgtemp + spring + summer + fall + 
    cloudcover + precip + weekday + dayType

Complete :
               (Intercept) hightemp lowtemp spring summer cloudcover precip
avgtemp          0         1/2      1/2       0      0      0          0   
fall             1           0        0      -1     -1      0          0   
dayTypeweekend   1           0        0       0      0      0          0   
               weekdayTRUE
avgtemp          0        
fall             0        
dayTypeweekend  -1        
alias(volume ~ ., railtrail_trim)

Model :
volume ~ avgtemp + spring + summer + cloudcover + precip + weekday

###diagnostic plots

these diagnostics are fine

0.18 (r^2) of the variation in volume is explained by avg temperature & residual standard error is high (over 100 out of 500)

add predictors to improve the model - weekday

###adding a categorical predictor

weekday appears to have an effect

-0.3 is evidence that weekday and volume are related

y = intercept + (m_avg_temp * avgtemp) + (m_weekday * weekday)

model_temp_weekday <- lm(volume ~ avgtemp + weekday, railtrail_trim)
plotModel(model_temp_weekday)

parallel lines denoting weekdays and weekends (TRUE and FALSE)

volume = intercept + (m_avg_temp * avg_temp) + (m_weekday * weekday)

when weekday is FALSE

volume = intercept + (m_avg_temp * avg_temp) + 0

###interactions

sometimes there will be a dependancy between independent predictors e.g summer and avg temp

`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

lines of best fit are different for avgtemp vs volume for weekdays and weekends

volume ~ avgtemp + weekday + avgtemp:weekday
